As 
<bibRefCitation author="Frey" box="[190,328,701,727]" firstAuthor="Frey" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="83 - 123" refId="ref9180" refString="Frey, D. G. (1980) On the plurality of Chydorus sphaericus (O. F. Muller) Cladocera, Chydoridae), and designation of a neotype from Sjaelso, Denmark. Hydrobiologia, 69 (1 - 2), 83 - 123." type="journal article" year="1980">Frey (1980)</bibRefCitation>
stated, the American representative of the 
<taxonomicName authority="(O. F. Muller)" baseAuthorityName="O. F. Muller" box="[826,1236,701,727]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Chydorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sphaericus">
<emphasis box="[826,1074,701,726]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Chydorus sphaericus</emphasis>
(O.F. Müller)
</taxonomicName>
complex, named 
<taxonomicName authority="Frey" authorityName="Frey" authorityYear="1980" box="[151,373,741,767]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Chydorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevilabris">
<emphasis box="[151,311,741,766]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. brevilabris</emphasis>
Frey
</taxonomicName>
, is widely distributed (from 
<collectingCountry box="[702,790,741,767]" name="Canada" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Canada</collectingCountry>
to northern 
<collectingCountry box="[932,1027,741,767]" name="Mexico" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Mexico</collectingCountry>
). A comparison with 
<taxonomicName box="[1275,1436,741,766]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Chydorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sphaericus">
<emphasis box="[1275,1436,741,766]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C. sphaericus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[215,324,781,807]" name="Germany" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Germany</collectingCountry>
revealed more than 17.61% divergence, confirming the true species status of both.
</paragraph>
